<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="../../assets/xml/rss.xsl" media="all"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>Carlos says "bla bla" (Unix)</title><link>http://carlosvin.github.io/</link><description></description><atom:link href="http://carlosvin.github.io/en/categories/unix.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><language>en</language><lastBuildDate>Fri, 12 Feb 2016 18:50:48 GMT</lastBuildDate><generator>https://getnikola.com/</generator><docs>http://blogs.law.harvard.edu/tech/rss</docs><item><title>Convert files formats: Windows to Unix</title><link>http://carlosvin.github.io/en/posts/recursive-dos-unix/</link><dc:creator>Carlos Martín Sánchez</dc:creator><description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;p&gt;If you are developing from a Windows environment to a Unix target environment, most likely you have had this issue:
You install source files in Windows format in your Unix environment.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a way quite simple to convert all your files from Windows to Unix format:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;pre class="code bash"&gt;&lt;a name="rest_code_f74c415484ed46f0b4da180ae3990390-1"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;find . -type f -print0 &lt;span class="p"&gt;|&lt;/span&gt; xargs -0 dos2unix
&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;p&gt;I got it, of course, form &lt;a class="reference external" href="http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11929461/how-can-i-run-dos2unix-on-an-entire-directory"&gt;http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11929461/how-can-i-run-dos2unix-on-an-entire-directory&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</description><category>Unix</category><category>Useful Commands</category><category>Windows</category><guid>http://carlosvin.github.io/en/posts/recursive-dos-unix/</guid><pubDate>Fri, 12 Feb 2016 09:34:00 GMT</pubDate></item></channel></rss>